00:10:40.670 --> 00:10:42.680 align:middle line:84%
With a mother who's
nursing a baby,

00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:45.320 align:middle line:84%
and there's like
maternal infant bonding,

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:46.850 align:middle line:90%
oxytocin is there for that.

00:10:46.850 --> 00:10:49.040 align:middle line:90%
>> I feel very benevolent.

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:53.600 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I feel as though I
have no enemies in the world.

00:10:53.600 --> 00:10:58.220 align:middle line:90%
And this is very lovely.

00:10:58.220 --> 00:11:01.070 align:middle line:84%
>> And that sense of oneness and
unity and connection signifies

00:11:01.070 --> 00:11:03.480 align:middle line:84%
sort of the peak of a
psychedelic experience.

00:11:03.480 --> 00:11:06.695 align:middle line:84%
And when you come away from
that, you come away changed.

00:11:06.695 --> 00:11:08.930 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:11:08.930 --> 00:11:11.780 align:middle line:10%
>> The insight that I was
getting from traditional

00:11:11.780 --> 00:11:16.040 align:middle line:10%
and classic Buddhist meditation
was similar to the insight that

00:11:16.040 --> 00:11:19.430 align:middle line:10%
I'd finally arrived
at under the acid.

00:11:19.430 --> 00:11:23.360 align:middle line:84%
The lesson was
form is emptiness.

00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:26.150 align:middle line:84%
There's a sense of
emptiness and transitoriness

00:11:26.150 --> 00:11:28.970 align:middle line:90%
in all perceived phenomena.

00:11:28.970 --> 00:11:31.670 align:middle line:84%
And there's no need
to get hysterically

00:11:31.670 --> 00:11:34.820 align:middle line:84%
hung up on any thought
form, no need to grab.

00:11:34.820 --> 00:11:39.350 align:middle line:84%
And there is no enlightenment,
no wisdom, no illumination,

00:11:39.350 --> 00:11:43.700 align:middle line:84%
no god, no identity, no
self, no reference point,

00:11:43.700 --> 00:11:47.263 align:middle line:84%
that any grabbing for a
reference point is vain.

00:11:47.263 --> 00:11:48.680 align:middle line:84%
And that's one of
the first things

00:11:48.680 --> 00:11:50.138 align:middle line:84%
you think when you
get high anyway,

00:11:50.138 --> 00:11:51.650 align:middle line:84%
that even if you
didn't get high,

00:11:51.650 --> 00:11:54.110 align:middle line:84%
you'd be seeing the same
reality, that in a sense,

00:11:54.110 --> 00:11:55.850 align:middle line:90%
acid is not necessary.

00:11:55.850 --> 00:11:58.481 align:middle line:90%
And that's why it's OK.

00:11:58.481 --> 00:12:01.820 align:middle line:90%
[HORN HONKS]

00:12:01.820 --> 00:12:05.990 align:middle line:84%
>> In the early 1950s, as LSD
research was in its infancy,

00:12:05.990 --> 00:12:08.810 align:middle line:84%
little was known in the West
about naturally-occurring

00:12:08.810 --> 00:12:10.760 align:middle line:90%
psychedelics.

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:13.730 align:middle line:84%
In 1953, author
Aldous Huxley was

00:12:13.730 --> 00:12:16.580 align:middle line:84%
given mescaline, the active
ingredient in the peyote

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:21.080 align:middle line:84%
cactus, under the supervision
of psychiatrist Humphry Osmond.

00:12:21.080 --> 00:12:24.470 align:middle line:84%
Huxley later wrote about this
experience in the seminal book

00:12:24.470 --> 00:12:26.660 align:middle line:90%
"The Doors of Perception."

00:12:26.660 --> 00:12:29.960 align:middle line:84%
And in New York City, a
very unlikely character

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:32.960 align:middle line:84%
helped bridge the gap between
the ancient traditions

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:35.735 align:middle line:90%
and modern America.

00:12:35.735 --> 00:12:39.960 align:middle line:10%
>> R. Gordon Wasson was a
very successful businessman

00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:40.760 align:middle line:10%
and banker.

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:43.910 align:middle line:10%
He was a vice
president of JP Morgan.

00:12:43.910 --> 00:12:47.510 align:middle line:84%
As a young man, he met his
future wife, Valentina,

00:12:47.510 --> 00:12:48.680 align:middle line:90%
who was Russian.

00:12:48.680 --> 00:12:53.540 align:middle line:10%
And she had a great interest and
enthusiasm for the collection

00:12:53.540 --> 00:12:55.970 align:middle line:10%
of edible mushrooms.

00:12:55.970 --> 00:12:58.700 align:middle line:84%
>> While on their honeymoon
in the Catskill Mountains,

00:12:58.700 --> 00:13:02.510 align:middle line:84%
Valentina leaped with excitement
after spying a cluster of wild

00:13:02.510 --> 00:13:05.480 align:middle line:90%
mushrooms growing in the forest.

00:13:05.480 --> 00:13:07.730 align:middle line:84%
She sounded off the
species name in Russian

00:13:07.730 --> 00:13:11.390 align:middle line:84%
and insisted that they prepare
them for dinner that night.

00:13:11.390 --> 00:13:14.780 align:middle line:84%
Wasson, of Anglo-Saxon
heritage, was brought up

00:13:14.780 --> 00:13:17.660 align:middle line:84%
to believe mushrooms were
poison and was horrified

00:13:17.660 --> 00:13:19.880 align:middle line:90%
at his wife's enthusiasm.

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:21.710 align:middle line:84%
This difference in
cultural attitudes

00:13:21.710 --> 00:13:25.610 align:middle line:84%
became the catalyst for Wasson's
lifelong interest in mycology,

00:13:25.610 --> 00:13:27.530 align:middle line:90%
or the study of fungi.

00:13:27.530 --> 00:13:30.860 align:middle line:84%
>> And then, in the early
'50s, a friend of his wrote him

00:13:30.860 --> 00:13:35.450 align:middle line:84%
a letter suggesting he look
into an extant mushroom cult

00:13:35.450 --> 00:13:37.830 align:middle line:84%
in the central
highlands of Mexico,

00:13:37.830 --> 00:13:41.885 align:middle line:84%
where he had heard that there
was use of hallucinogenic

00:13:41.885 --> 00:13:42.685 align:middle line:90%
mushrooms.

00:13:42.685 --> 00:13:45.290 align:middle line:84%
Now, this came as quite
a surprise to Wasson

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:47.300 align:middle line:84%
because at this
time, the early '50s,

00:13:47.300 --> 00:13:49.940 align:middle line:84%
it was not believed that
there were such things

00:13:49.940 --> 00:13:53.710 align:middle line:90%
as hallucinogenic mushrooms.

00:13:53.710 --> 00:13:59.410 align:middle line:10%
>> We went into the Mazatec
area far from the highways,

00:13:59.410 --> 00:14:01.570 align:middle line:10%
remote from Mexico City.

00:14:01.570 --> 00:14:04.120 align:middle line:84%
There we found that
rotten bagasse,

00:14:04.120 --> 00:14:07.520 align:middle line:84%
as it's called, bagasso,
covered with mushrooms.

00:14:07.520 --> 00:14:10.870 align:middle line:84%
These mushrooms I didn't
know, had never seen.

00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:13.450 align:middle line:90%
They were the sacred mushrooms.

00:14:13.450 --> 00:14:15.940 align:middle line:84%
>> After much difficulty,
and by some accounts,

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:18.460 align:middle line:84%
manipulation on
the part of Wasson,

00:14:18.460 --> 00:14:23.110 align:middle line:84%
he eventually found entry into
a velada, or mushroom ceremony.

00:14:23.110 --> 00:14:25.630 align:middle line:84%
The curandera, or
healer, was a woman

00:14:25.630 --> 00:14:28.030 align:middle line:84%
named Maria Sabina,
who represented

00:14:28.030 --> 00:14:30.250 align:middle line:84%
a long line of
underground healers

00:14:30.250 --> 00:14:33.400 align:middle line:84%
left intact since the
days of Spanish conquest.

00:14:33.400 --> 00:14:35.950 align:middle line:90%
[MUSICAL CHANTING]

00:14:35.950 --> 00:14:40.000 align:middle line:84%
>> And we were seeing
incredible sights.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.670 align:middle line:84%
All your senses
are rendered acute.

00:14:42.670 --> 00:14:44.890 align:middle line:90%
We say that you see visions.

00:14:44.890 --> 00:14:46.630 align:middle line:90%
You see hallucinations.

00:14:46.630 --> 00:14:49.450 align:middle line:84%
But that doesn't begin
to tell the story.

00:14:49.450 --> 00:14:51.520 align:middle line:84%
The hallucinations
are only part of it.

00:14:51.520 --> 00:14:52.870 align:middle line:90%
You hear sounds.

00:14:52.870 --> 00:14:54.190 align:middle line:90%
You smell things.

00:14:54.190 --> 00:14:58.171 align:middle line:90%
The night was thrilling.

00:14:58.171 --> 00:15:00.606 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:15:00.606 --> 00:15:04.510 align:middle line:90%


00:15:04.510 --> 00:15:07.960 align:middle line:10%
>> The visions were not
blurred or uncertain.

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:10.960 align:middle line:10%
I felt that I was
now seeing plain,

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:15.820 align:middle line:10%
whereas ordinary vision
gives us an imperfect view.

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:19.450 align:middle line:84%
I was seeing the archetypes,
the Platonic ideas

00:15:19.450 --> 00:15:25.210 align:middle line:84%
that underlie the imperfect
images of everyday life.

00:15:25.210 --> 00:15:27.430 align:middle line:90%
The thought crossed my mind.

00:15:27.430 --> 00:15:29.560 align:middle line:84%
Could the divine
mushrooms be the secret

00:15:29.560 --> 00:15:31.660 align:middle line:84%
that lay behind the
ancient mysteries?

00:15:31.660 --> 00:15:35.660 align:middle line:90%


00:15:35.660 --> 00:15:37.880 align:middle line:84%
Could the miraculous
mobility that I was now

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:41.300 align:middle line:84%
enjoying be the explanation
for the flying witches that

00:15:41.300 --> 00:15:44.060 align:middle line:84%
played so important a part
in the folklore and fairy

00:15:44.060 --> 00:15:46.950 align:middle line:90%
tales of northern Europe?

00:15:46.950 --> 00:15:50.160 align:middle line:84%
These reflections passed through
my mind at the very same time

00:15:50.160 --> 00:15:52.050 align:middle line:90%
that I was seeing the visions.

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:54.060 align:middle line:84%
For the effect of
the mushrooms is

00:15:54.060 --> 00:15:58.050 align:middle line:84%
to bring about a vision of the
spirit, a split in the person,

00:15:58.050 --> 00:16:01.510 align:middle line:90%
a kind of schizophrenia.

00:16:01.510 --> 00:16:04.300 align:middle line:84%
>> Unbeknownst to Wasson,
his trips to Mexico were

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:07.450 align:middle line:84%
infiltrated by a group with
more nefarious interests

00:16:07.450 --> 00:16:10.150 align:middle line:84%
in the mind-altering
effects of psychedelics.

00:16:10.150 --> 00:16:12.430 align:middle line:84%
>> In their neverending
search for the miracle weapon,

00:16:12.430 --> 00:16:15.730 align:middle line:84%
CIA operatives searched here
in the remote mountain areas

00:16:15.730 --> 00:16:18.910 align:middle line:84%
of southern Mexico for what
up to then had been considered

00:16:18.910 --> 00:16:21.010 align:middle line:90%
a myth, magic mushrooms.

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:25.240 align:middle line:10%
>> And so Gordon Wasson was
unwittingly participating

00:16:25.240 --> 00:16:29.830 align:middle line:10%
in this sort of military
use of psychedelics.

00:16:29.830 --> 00:16:33.430 align:middle line:84%
>> They used this man, a
part-time chemist with the CIA,

00:16:33.430 --> 00:16:36.160 align:middle line:84%
to dupe this man, a
vice president of a bank

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:38.980 align:middle line:84%
and an amateur mycologist,
or mushroom expert,

00:16:38.980 --> 00:16:41.320 align:middle line:84%
to try to get to the magic
mushrooms and turn them

00:16:41.320 --> 00:16:42.183 align:middle line:90%
into a drug.

00:16:42.183 --> 00:16:44.350 align:middle line:84%
>> They gave it to several
different chemists to try

00:16:44.350 --> 00:16:48.470 align:middle line:84%
to figure out what was in it,
and nobody could figure it out.

00:16:48.470 --> 00:16:50.440 align:middle line:84%
And so they called
on Albert Hofmann,

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:52.540 align:middle line:90%
since he had invented LSD.

00:16:52.540 --> 00:16:54.220 align:middle line:84%
And they asked him
could he figure out

00:16:54.220 --> 00:16:57.610 align:middle line:84%
what was in the mushroom
that made it so psychedelic.

00:16:57.610 --> 00:17:00.190 align:middle line:84%
>> It would be the amateur,
R. Gordon Wasson and his

00:17:00.190 --> 00:17:03.250 align:middle line:84%
colleagues, who would win
the race and develop the drug

00:17:03.250 --> 00:17:07.869 align:middle line:84%
psilocybin from the
magic mushrooms.

00:17:07.869 --> 00:17:12.130 align:middle line:10%
>> I think that is very
strange that LSD is not just

00:17:12.130 --> 00:17:13.810 align:middle line:10%
a laboratory product.

00:17:13.810 --> 00:17:19.420 align:middle line:10%
It is closely related with
this old Indian magic drug.

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:24.250 align:middle line:10%
That means that LSD belongs
pharmacologically, chemically,

00:17:24.250 --> 00:17:28.280 align:middle line:10%
to the group of the sacred
magic plants of Mexico.

00:17:28.280 --> 00:17:31.750 align:middle line:10%
It's a very important finding.

00:17:31.750 --> 00:17:34.780 align:middle line:84%
>> Wasson was friends
with Henry Boothe Luce,

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:37.090 align:middle line:84%
who was the publisher
of "Life Magazine."

00:17:37.090 --> 00:17:40.030 align:middle line:84%
He told his friend Luce
about his experience,

00:17:40.030 --> 00:17:43.180 align:middle line:84%
and Luce encouraged him
to write up his account.

00:17:43.180 --> 00:17:47.350 align:middle line:84%
That was really the first word
out to Western civilization

00:17:47.350 --> 00:17:50.680 align:middle line:84%
that psychedelic mushrooms
indeed existed at all.

00:17:50.680 --> 00:17:53.950 align:middle line:10%
And it really stimulated
growing interest

00:17:53.950 --> 00:17:57.910 align:middle line:10%
and led to the psychedelic
explosion of the '60s.

00:17:57.910 --> 00:18:01.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Wasson's influence became due
in large part to an enigmatic

00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:05.050 align:middle line:84%
Harvard psychologist
named Timothy Leary.

00:18:05.050 --> 00:18:08.680 align:middle line:84%
Though he became known as the
most dangerous man in America,

00:18:08.680 --> 00:18:12.100 align:middle line:84%
he might have been described
by others in the year 1960

00:18:12.100 --> 00:18:15.700 align:middle line:84%
as a New England square,
a hard-drinking Irishman,

00:18:15.700 --> 00:18:19.240 align:middle line:84%
or by himself, an atheist
psychologist in the midst

00:18:19.240 --> 00:18:20.980 align:middle line:90%
of a midlife crisis.

00:18:20.980 --> 00:18:23.840 align:middle line:84%
>> Timothy Leary was a
very prominent researcher

00:18:23.840 --> 00:18:24.640 align:middle line:90%
at Harvard.

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:27.460 align:middle line:84%
His California
Personality Inventory

00:18:27.460 --> 00:18:29.510 align:middle line:90%
is still being used today.

00:18:29.510 --> 00:18:32.370 align:middle line:10%
He was sort of a pied piper.

00:18:32.370 --> 00:18:34.410 align:middle line:84%
>> During his early
years at Harvard,

00:18:34.410 --> 00:18:37.830 align:middle line:84%
Leary was in the throes
of personal crisis.

00:18:37.830 --> 00:18:41.520 align:middle line:84%
His first wife had committed
suicide on his 35th birthday,

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:45.870 align:middle line:84%
reportedly after a
strained open marriage.

00:18:45.870 --> 00:18:48.140 align:middle line:84%
It was during this time
that he described himself

00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:51.410 align:middle line:84%
as an anonymous
institutional employee who

00:18:51.410 --> 00:18:55.130 align:middle line:84%
drove to work each morning in
a long line of commuter cars

00:18:55.130 --> 00:18:58.010 align:middle line:84%
and drove home each
night and drank Martinis,

00:18:58.010 --> 00:19:00.140 align:middle line:84%
like several million
middle-class,

00:19:00.140 --> 00:19:02.660 align:middle line:90%
liberal, intellectual robots.

00:19:02.660 --> 00:19:04.512 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:19:04.512 --> 00:19:06.830 align:middle line:90%


00:19:06.830 --> 00:19:10.760 align:middle line:84%
Inspired by Wasson's article,
Leary traveled down to Mexico

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:13.400 align:middle line:84%
with a colleague in
1960 who had found

00:19:13.400 --> 00:19:17.140 align:middle line:84%
some mushrooms from a
curandero in the mountains.

00:19:17.140 --> 00:19:19.030 align:middle line:84%
Leary later said
that he learned more

00:19:19.030 --> 00:19:21.190 align:middle line:84%
about the brain and
its possibilities,

00:19:21.190 --> 00:19:24.130 align:middle line:84%
and more about psychology,
in the five hours

00:19:24.130 --> 00:19:27.670 align:middle line:84%
after taking the mushrooms
than he had in the preceding 15

00:19:27.670 --> 00:19:31.870 align:middle line:84%
years of studying and doing
research in psychology.

00:19:31.870 --> 00:19:36.040 align:middle line:10%
>> When he got back to Harvard,
he got permission to do

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:38.080 align:middle line:10%
research with psilocybin.

00:19:38.080 --> 00:19:40.850 align:middle line:84%
>> And that was the beginning of
the Harvard Psilocybin Research

00:19:40.850 --> 00:19:41.650 align:middle line:90%
Project.

00:19:41.650 --> 00:19:43.210 align:middle line:10%
And that was really
the beginning

00:19:43.210 --> 00:19:46.210 align:middle line:10%
of formal research,
attempted clinical research,

00:19:46.210 --> 00:19:48.527 align:middle line:10%
of psychedelic agents
in the United States.

00:19:48.527 --> 00:19:50.860 align:middle line:84%
>> Timothy Leary had two
research products that could go

00:19:50.860 --> 00:19:53.520 align:middle line:84%
to the Harvard Psilocybin
Research Program.

00:19:53.520 --> 00:19:55.490 align:middle line:84%
It was a Good Friday
study with Walter Pahnke.

00:19:55.490 --> 00:19:59.320 align:middle line:10%
It was a remarkable
study and groundbreaking.

00:19:59.320 --> 00:20:02.080 align:middle line:84%
They had given
psilocybin and a placebo

00:20:02.080 --> 00:20:04.600 align:middle line:84%
to 20 graduate
students in theology,

00:20:04.600 --> 00:20:08.110 align:middle line:84%
comparing their experiences to
genuine mystical experiences

00:20:08.110 --> 00:20:10.630 align:middle line:84%
found throughout millennia,
through mystics and saints.

00:20:10.630 --> 00:20:13.930 align:middle line:84%
>> They arranged to have
access to the Marsh Chapel.

00:20:13.930 --> 00:20:15.760 align:middle line:90%
It was Good Friday.

00:20:15.760 --> 00:20:18.520 align:middle line:90%
They were in a basement chapel.

00:20:18.520 --> 00:20:22.360 align:middle line:10%
And the service from
upstairs in the main chapel

00:20:22.360 --> 00:20:23.575 align:middle line:10%
was being piped through.

00:20:23.575 --> 00:20:25.375 align:middle line:90%
[ORGAN PLAYING]

00:20:25.375 --> 00:20:29.340 align:middle line:90%


00:20:29.340 --> 00:20:31.860 align:middle line:84%
>> The Reverend Howard
Thurman was the minister,

00:20:31.860 --> 00:20:34.050 align:middle line:84%
who was Martin Luther
King's mentor--

00:20:34.050 --> 00:20:38.730 align:middle line:84%
this incredible dynamic
speaker, orator.

00:20:38.730 --> 00:20:45.660 align:middle line:10%
>> You, Pilate, standing for
Rome, are the universal coward.

00:20:45.660 --> 00:20:51.120 align:middle line:84%
I, standing for the kingdom of
God, have braved everything,

00:20:51.120 --> 00:20:59.460 align:middle line:84%
lost everything, and
won an eternal crown.

00:20:59.460 --> 00:21:01.950 align:middle line:84%
>> They developed a scale
of mystical experience.

00:21:01.950 --> 00:21:04.890 align:middle line:84%
Some of the items are a noetic
quality, intuitive quality

00:21:04.890 --> 00:21:08.160 align:middle line:84%
of understanding things,
transcendence of time and space

00:21:08.160 --> 00:21:10.930 align:middle line:84%
as we know it, a sense of
unity with all living things

00:21:10.930 --> 00:21:14.290 align:middle line:90%
internally as well.

00:21:14.290 --> 00:21:15.130 align:middle line:90%
>> I shall die.

00:21:15.130 --> 00:21:18.560 align:middle line:90%


00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:22.245 align:middle line:84%
But that is all that
I shall do for death.

00:21:22.245 --> 00:21:27.320 align:middle line:90%


00:21:27.320 --> 00:21:30.320 align:middle line:84%
>> Of the 20
experimental students,

00:21:30.320 --> 00:21:33.230 align:middle line:84%
nine out of the 20 people
had a mystical experience.

00:21:33.230 --> 00:21:36.140 align:middle line:84%
And eight out of those
nine had the psilocybin.

00:21:36.140 --> 00:21:38.600 align:middle line:84%
>> It was the first study
showing that these agents,

00:21:38.600 --> 00:21:40.310 align:middle line:84%
these medicines,
these sacraments,

00:21:40.310 --> 00:21:43.670 align:middle line:84%
can produce an experience that
was found throughout millennia

00:21:43.670 --> 00:21:46.160 align:middle line:90%
in various religious traditions.

00:21:46.160 --> 00:21:49.058 align:middle line:10%
>> One young man had
a kind of nervous--

00:21:49.058 --> 00:21:50.600 align:middle line:10%
I was going to say
nervous breakdown,

00:21:50.600 --> 00:21:52.520 align:middle line:10%
but it was actually
positive for him.

00:21:52.520 --> 00:21:55.850 align:middle line:10%
So he was so blown away by
this spiritual experience

00:21:55.850 --> 00:21:58.190 align:middle line:10%
he was having that he kind
of ran out of the chapel.

00:21:58.190 --> 00:21:59.898 align:middle line:84%
And he was trying to
run to the, I think,

00:21:59.898 --> 00:22:02.780 align:middle line:84%
the dean or the president's
office to proclaim everything

00:22:02.780 --> 00:22:03.950 align:middle line:90%
that he had learned.

00:22:03.950 --> 00:22:08.660 align:middle line:84%
>> And behaved rather bizarrely
out in public until the sitters

00:22:08.660 --> 00:22:11.510 align:middle line:84%
found him and retrieved
him and brought him back.

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:15.440 align:middle line:84%
>> And he actually had to be
sedated with a tranquilizer.

00:22:15.440 --> 00:22:17.900 align:middle line:84%
So that's kind of an
interesting piece of history

00:22:17.900 --> 00:22:19.040 align:middle line:90%
that didn't get reported.

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:20.904 align:middle line:10%
