insight and can be
used in psychotherapy.

00:22:53.140 --> 00:22:56.890 align:middle line:10%
>> So it's a really unique
history in the area of drug

00:22:56.890 --> 00:23:00.940 align:middle line:10%
research in that there was a
heyday of psychedelic research

00:23:00.940 --> 00:23:05.500 align:middle line:10%
extending from the 1950s
through the early '70s.

00:23:05.500 --> 00:23:08.200 align:middle line:84%
>> Back then, any psychiatric
researcher or clinician could

00:23:08.200 --> 00:23:12.230 align:middle line:84%
write Sandoz to get a sample
of LSD to test it or to use it

00:23:12.230 --> 00:23:13.030 align:middle line:90%
clinically.

00:23:13.030 --> 00:23:14.860 align:middle line:90%
It was legal and available.

00:23:14.860 --> 00:23:17.500 align:middle line:84%
And that really began
the big experiment

00:23:17.500 --> 00:23:21.430 align:middle line:84%
with LSD that lasted
close to 30 years.

00:23:21.430 --> 00:23:23.860 align:middle line:10%
>> In carefully
controlled experiments,

00:23:23.860 --> 00:23:26.980 align:middle line:10%
interesting results have been
reported on the therapeutic use

00:23:26.980 --> 00:23:31.270 align:middle line:10%
of LSD with the mentally
ill, the drug addict,

00:23:31.270 --> 00:23:35.440 align:middle line:10%
the terminal cancer patient, and
in the VA hospital in Topeka,

00:23:35.440 --> 00:23:40.120 align:middle line:10%
Kansas, a special research
program for alcoholics.

00:23:40.120 --> 00:23:41.830 align:middle line:84%
>> We bring them
in on one Monday,

00:23:41.830 --> 00:23:45.760 align:middle line:84%
and they spend one week of
getting acquainted and having

00:23:45.760 --> 00:23:48.820 align:middle line:84%
all the tests and
examinations done.

00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:52.570 align:middle line:84%
The second Monday, we
give them a small dose

00:23:52.570 --> 00:23:56.320 align:middle line:84%
of LSD in the five-man
ward, together.

00:23:56.320 --> 00:24:00.190 align:middle line:84%
Then, the third Monday,
we give them a larger dose

00:24:00.190 --> 00:24:03.940 align:middle line:84%
individually and have
each one of them cared

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:06.940 align:middle line:90%
for by one of these teams.

00:24:06.940 --> 00:24:10.330 align:middle line:84%
And this is where we aim for
the so-called psychedelic

00:24:10.330 --> 00:24:11.980 align:middle line:90%
experience.

00:24:11.980 --> 00:24:14.770 align:middle line:84%
>> The best clinical outcomes
are with subjects who,

00:24:14.770 --> 00:24:18.040 align:middle line:84%
during the course of what
was often just a one-session

00:24:18.040 --> 00:24:22.510 align:middle line:84%
treatment, during that session,
had a psychospiritual epiphany,

00:24:22.510 --> 00:24:24.460 align:middle line:90%
a mystical-level experience.

00:24:24.460 --> 00:24:27.830 align:middle line:84%
>> I know I kept fighting
the religious music.

00:24:27.830 --> 00:24:31.090 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know why
then, but Dr. Koren

00:24:31.090 --> 00:24:36.040 align:middle line:84%
kept urging me to find out
why I was fighting this.

00:24:36.040 --> 00:24:38.755 align:middle line:84%
And I remember I was just
really scared to death.

00:24:38.755 --> 00:24:40.459 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:24:40.459 --> 00:24:43.770 align:middle line:90%


00:24:43.770 --> 00:24:46.800 align:middle line:84%
And I just reached up,
and it was like somebody

00:24:46.800 --> 00:24:48.930 align:middle line:90%
grabbed me and brought me up.

00:24:48.930 --> 00:24:52.840 align:middle line:90%


00:24:52.840 --> 00:24:58.290 align:middle line:84%
And I interpret this as for
the first time in my life,

00:24:58.290 --> 00:25:00.120 align:middle line:90%
I wanted love.

00:25:00.120 --> 00:25:03.710 align:middle line:84%
And I think this is the thing
that was probably my biggest

00:25:03.710 --> 00:25:06.348 align:middle line:84%
problem is that I thought
everybody was forcing it on me,

00:25:06.348 --> 00:25:07.640 align:middle line:90%
and I wasn't going to let them.

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:10.530 align:middle line:90%


00:25:10.530 --> 00:25:15.120 align:middle line:10%
>> The amazing thing about LSD
is very much its evolutionary

00:25:15.120 --> 00:25:18.480 align:middle line:10%
nature, is that it seems
to concentrate in areas

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:22.740 align:middle line:10%
of the brain that relate to
mammalian and reptilian stages

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:25.380 align:middle line:10%
of evolutionary development
which are then experienced

00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:29.160 align:middle line:10%
by the person, the fact also
that people become aware

00:25:29.160 --> 00:25:33.000 align:middle line:10%
of the fact that man is not
just a single-dimensional being

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:36.730 align:middle line:10%
in a physical body but
exists as a being over many,

00:25:36.730 --> 00:25:39.570 align:middle line:10%
many lifetimes at many levels
of consciousness beyond

00:25:39.570 --> 00:25:41.070 align:middle line:10%
the physical.

00:25:41.070 --> 00:25:43.500 align:middle line:84%
And I do feel that,
in the future,

00:25:43.500 --> 00:25:45.270 align:middle line:84%
there will be
centers where people

00:25:45.270 --> 00:25:48.570 align:middle line:84%
will be able to go to prepare
people for any kind of turning

00:25:48.570 --> 00:25:51.150 align:middle line:84%
point or crisis in their
life, such as along the lines

00:25:51.150 --> 00:25:53.550 align:middle line:84%
of the incredible
powerful research

00:25:53.550 --> 00:25:56.740 align:middle line:84%
that Stan Grof and Walter Pahnke
did at Spring Grove Hospital

00:25:56.740 --> 00:25:57.990 align:middle line:90%
with terminal cancer patients.

00:25:57.990 --> 00:26:01.030 align:middle line:90%


00:26:01.030 --> 00:26:03.960 align:middle line:84%
>> This is a mental institution,
Spring Grove State Hospital

00:26:03.960 --> 00:26:05.190 align:middle line:90%
in Baltimore.

00:26:05.190 --> 00:26:07.260 align:middle line:84%
It is one of four places
in the country where

00:26:07.260 --> 00:26:09.480 align:middle line:84%
research on LSD
treatment continues

00:26:09.480 --> 00:26:11.280 align:middle line:90%
under federal sponsorship.

00:26:11.280 --> 00:26:15.330 align:middle line:84%
The tablets in Ott's hand each
contain a microscopic trace

00:26:15.330 --> 00:26:16.950 align:middle line:90%
of LSD.

00:26:16.950 --> 00:26:20.280 align:middle line:84%
To an observer, the atmosphere
seems closer to faith healing

00:26:20.280 --> 00:26:21.390 align:middle line:90%
than medicine.

00:26:21.390 --> 00:26:24.690 align:middle line:84%
>> So the way in which they
really refined the approach is

00:26:24.690 --> 00:26:28.440 align:middle line:84%
that they used a two-person
team, often a male-female.

00:26:28.440 --> 00:26:31.470 align:middle line:10%
They pioneered eight-hour
therapy sessions, sometimes

00:26:31.470 --> 00:26:33.100 align:middle line:10%
even longer.

00:26:33.100 --> 00:26:37.050 align:middle line:84%
It was this very expressive,
supportive environment.

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:40.440 align:middle line:10%
>> It isn't so much the drug
as the drug in the context

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:43.410 align:middle line:10%
in which it's used,
the expectations,

00:26:43.410 --> 00:26:46.020 align:middle line:10%
how the person is held
safely while they're under

00:26:46.020 --> 00:26:48.480 align:middle line:10%
the influence of it, and the
interpretation that's made

00:26:48.480 --> 00:26:49.830 align:middle line:10%
afterwards.

00:26:49.830 --> 00:26:51.840 align:middle line:90%
>> I was here under LSD.

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:55.680 align:middle line:84%
This went on for a million
miles on both sides,

00:26:55.680 --> 00:27:00.000 align:middle line:84%
an endless deep
and eternity onto.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:03.360 align:middle line:84%
And it was just one of
the fears I had buried,

00:27:03.360 --> 00:27:06.030 align:middle line:84%
and it was a fear
of being left alone.

00:27:06.030 --> 00:27:08.220 align:middle line:84%
>> We get very stuck in
our ways and sort of rigid

00:27:08.220 --> 00:27:09.150 align:middle line:90%
in our thinking.

00:27:09.150 --> 00:27:10.692 align:middle line:10%
One of the things
the psychedelics do

00:27:10.692 --> 00:27:13.860 align:middle line:10%
is they increase
cognitive flexibility.

00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:16.620 align:middle line:10%
You become less rigid in
how you think they quiet

00:27:16.620 --> 00:27:19.140 align:middle line:10%
down the default
mode network, which

00:27:19.140 --> 00:27:23.390 align:middle line:10%
is sort of the self-obsessed,
self-serving, how am I doing?

00:27:23.390 --> 00:27:24.190 align:middle line:90%
Who am I?

00:27:24.190 --> 00:27:25.730 align:middle line:90%
Am I liked?

00:27:25.730 --> 00:27:26.730 align:middle line:90%
What did I do yesterday?

00:27:26.730 --> 00:27:28.022 align:middle line:90%
What am I going to do tomorrow?

00:27:28.022 --> 00:27:31.050 align:middle line:84%
And the psychedelics sort
of quiet this narcissism

00:27:31.050 --> 00:27:34.440 align:middle line:84%
and neuroticism and allow
other parts of the brain

00:27:34.440 --> 00:27:37.320 align:middle line:84%
to get more active or to
connect with each other.

00:27:37.320 --> 00:27:38.820 align:middle line:90%
>> I feel beautiful.

00:27:38.820 --> 00:27:40.170 align:middle line:90%
>> All right.

00:27:40.170 --> 00:27:43.020 align:middle line:84%
>> I feel squashed
with beautiful.

00:27:43.020 --> 00:27:46.290 align:middle line:90%


00:27:46.290 --> 00:27:50.940 align:middle line:84%
>> That's a really powerful,
useful experience to have.

00:27:50.940 --> 00:27:53.550 align:middle line:84%
And it can help people
out of a dark place.

00:27:53.550 --> 00:27:55.440 align:middle line:84%
>> If you hadn't
been prepared for it,

00:27:55.440 --> 00:27:59.160 align:middle line:84%
if you hadn't gone through
those weeks of preparation,

00:27:59.160 --> 00:28:02.070 align:middle line:90%
would LSD have meant as much?

00:28:02.070 --> 00:28:06.420 align:middle line:84%
>> If I was ill before, I would
have been ill, it seems to me,

00:28:06.420 --> 00:28:08.160 align:middle line:90%
beyond repair.

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:12.540 align:middle line:84%
I would have been so
frightened without the guidance

00:28:12.540 --> 00:28:14.640 align:middle line:84%
and the trust and
the preparation.

00:28:14.640 --> 00:28:16.665 align:middle line:84%
It would have been
a tragedy, horrible.

00:28:16.665 --> 00:28:24.140 align:middle line:90%


00:28:24.140 --> 00:28:28.580 align:middle line:84%
>> I got interested in LSD
therapy when I was in two-year

00:28:28.580 --> 00:28:32.240 align:middle line:84%
public health service at the
public health prison hospital

00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:34.590 align:middle line:90%
in Lexington, Kentucky.

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:37.170 align:middle line:84%
At that time, there was
really no good treatment

00:28:37.170 --> 00:28:39.090 align:middle line:90%
for narcotic addiction.

00:28:39.090 --> 00:28:41.550 align:middle line:84%
Recidivism rate was
extraordinarily high.

00:28:41.550 --> 00:28:45.900 align:middle line:84%
I think people leaving Lexington
had a 90% relapse rate.

00:28:45.900 --> 00:28:49.960 align:middle line:84%
And I had read about the
studies with alcoholism.

00:28:49.960 --> 00:28:52.890 align:middle line:84%
And I thought
perhaps LSD might be

00:28:52.890 --> 00:28:57.660 align:middle line:84%
useful to provide some lasting
change for narcotic addiction.

00:28:57.660 --> 00:29:00.720 align:middle line:84%
In looking at the
literature at that time,

00:29:00.720 --> 00:29:02.940 align:middle line:84%
it looked like
that therapists who

00:29:02.940 --> 00:29:09.030 align:middle line:84%
had used LSD themselves got much
better results than therapists

00:29:09.030 --> 00:29:11.200 align:middle line:90%
who had not used LSD themselves.

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:14.370 align:middle line:84%
So I decided to do
a controlled study.

00:29:14.370 --> 00:29:19.140 align:middle line:10%
I would give LSD to a group of
narcotic addicts at Lexington

00:29:19.140 --> 00:29:22.650 align:middle line:10%
who volunteered for the study,
without having ever taken LSD

00:29:22.650 --> 00:29:27.600 align:middle line:10%
myself, to see what impact
that the experience might have

00:29:27.600 --> 00:29:30.270 align:middle line:10%
on their relation
with other prisoners,

00:29:30.270 --> 00:29:34.900 align:middle line:10%
with authority figures, with
insight about themselves.

00:29:34.900 --> 00:29:38.850 align:middle line:10%
And then, my plan was to
then take the LSD myself

00:29:38.850 --> 00:29:42.720 align:middle line:10%
under supervision from staff at
the Addiction Research Center

00:29:42.720 --> 00:29:45.540 align:middle line:10%
there who were
experienced with the agent

00:29:45.540 --> 00:29:48.690 align:middle line:10%
and do a second group.

00:29:48.690 --> 00:29:51.920 align:middle line:84%
But unfortunately, when I
was getting ready to do that,

00:29:51.920 --> 00:29:56.930 align:middle line:84%
the company that made LSD,
Sandoz, decided to recall it.

00:29:56.930 --> 00:30:02.270 align:middle line:84%
This was around 1965,
1966, because LSD

00:30:02.270 --> 00:30:04.004 align:middle line:90%
had become a street drug.

00:30:04.004 --> 00:30:06.374 align:middle line:90%
[HORNS BLARING]

00:30:06.374 --> 00:30:11.120 align:middle line:90%


00:30:11.120 --> 00:30:14.570 align:middle line:10%
>> And on streets like this,
transactions involving me take

00:30:14.570 --> 00:30:16.720 align:middle line:10%
place all the time--

00:30:16.720 --> 00:30:20.450 align:middle line:10%
illegal, of course, but
my tabs and caps and sugar

00:30:20.450 --> 00:30:23.840 align:middle line:10%
cubes that dissolve in your
mind as well as your mouth

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:26.180 align:middle line:10%
are selling every day.

00:30:26.180 --> 00:30:31.280 align:middle line:84%
Drop a cap on me,
man, and drop out.

00:30:31.280 --> 00:30:36.080 align:middle line:84%
But watch it, because the
trip can be a trap, too.

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:39.680 align:middle line:84%
You never know where a
ticket with me will take you.

00:30:39.680 --> 00:30:41.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Just as pioneers of
psychedelic research were

00:30:41.900 --> 00:30:44.720 align:middle line:84%
beginning to understand
its therapeutic potential,

00:30:44.720 --> 00:30:48.320 align:middle line:84%
LSD began to leak out
of the laboratory.

00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:51.080 align:middle line:84%
The two figures most
responsible for its expansion

00:30:51.080 --> 00:30:54.890 align:middle line:84%
into the American culture lived
on opposite ends of the country

00:30:54.890 --> 00:30:57.740 align:middle line:84%
and were from equally
different backgrounds.

00:30:57.740 --> 00:31:00.980 align:middle line:84%
On the West Coast, Ken
Kesey was introduced to LSD

00:31:00.980 --> 00:31:06.260 align:middle line:84%
in the late 1950s as part of
the CIA's MK-Ultra program.

00:31:06.260 --> 00:31:08.370 align:middle line:84%
>> At the time, I was
training for the Olympics.

00:31:08.370 --> 00:31:09.990 align:middle line:90%
I made it to be an alternate.

00:31:09.990 --> 00:31:10.790 align:middle line:90%
>> As a wrestler?

00:31:10.790 --> 00:31:11.780 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, as a wrestler.

00:31:11.780 --> 00:31:15.020 align:middle line:10%
I'd never been drunk on beer,
let alone done any drugs.

00:31:15.020 --> 00:31:17.030 align:middle line:10%
But this is the
American government.

00:31:17.030 --> 00:31:18.990 align:middle line:84%
I had a neighbor who
was a psychologist.

00:31:18.990 --> 00:31:21.390 align:middle line:84%
He was booked to do the
experiments that Tuesday.

00:31:21.390 --> 00:31:22.190 align:middle line:90%
He chickened out.

00:31:22.190 --> 00:31:23.570 align:middle line:84%
He says, you want
to do them? $20.

00:31:23.570 --> 00:31:24.110 align:middle line:90%
Show up.

00:31:24.110 --> 00:31:25.020 align:middle line:90%
They gave them to me.

00:31:25.020 --> 00:31:28.963 align:middle line:84%
I did them on every Tuesday
for six or eight months.

00:31:28.963 --> 00:31:31.130 align:middle line:84%
The government wanted
somebody to look in that room.

00:31:31.130 --> 00:31:32.270 align:middle line:84%
They said, hey, we
got a great room.

00:31:32.270 --> 00:31:33.830 align:middle line:90%
We discovered this nice room.

00:31:33.830 --> 00:31:36.320 align:middle line:84%
Let's get somebody to go
in there and look it over.

00:31:36.320 --> 00:31:38.480 align:middle line:10%
>> Kesey would go on
to write "One Flew over

00:31:38.480 --> 00:31:41.930 align:middle line:10%
the Cuckoo's Nest" partly
based on these experiences,

00:31:41.930 --> 00:31:45.380 align:middle line:10%
and later, to host the so-called
acid tests with the Merry

00:31:45.380 --> 00:31:46.250 align:middle line:10%
Pranksters.

00:31:46.250 --> 00:31:49.370 align:middle line:84%
>> And by that time, the
government had said, OK,

00:31:49.370 --> 00:31:50.303 align:middle line:90%
stop that experiment.

00:31:50.303 --> 00:31:52.970 align:middle line:84%
All these guinea pigs that we've
sent up there into outer space,

00:31:52.970 --> 00:31:54.410 align:middle line:84%
bring them back
down, and don't ever

00:31:54.410 --> 00:31:56.452 align:middle line:84%
let them go back up there
again, because we don't

00:31:56.452 --> 00:31:57.840 align:middle line:90%
like the look in their eyes.

00:31:57.840 --> 00:32:02.630 align:middle line:10%
>> I give the CIA total credit
for sponsoring and initiating

00:32:02.630 --> 00:32:06.830 align:middle line:10%
the entire consciousness
movement counterculture events

00:32:06.830 --> 00:32:08.330 align:middle line:10%
of the 1960s.

00:32:08.330 --> 00:32:10.580 align:middle line:84%
>> And on the East
Coast was Timothy Leary,

00:32:10.580 --> 00:32:13.340 align:middle line:84%
the now-former
Harvard psychologist.

00:32:13.340 --> 00:32:16.620 align:middle line:84%
>> He began to distribute
the drug beyond his research

00:32:16.620 --> 00:32:17.420 align:middle line:90%
subjects.

00:32:17.420 --> 00:32:20.090 align:middle line:84%
He began to speak quite
openly to the press.

00:32:20.090 --> 00:32:23.810 align:middle line:84%
>> He signed an agreement
promising that he would not

00:32:23.810 --> 00:32:27.770 align:middle line:84%
give it to any undergraduate
students but only to graduate

00:32:27.770 --> 00:32:32.570 align:middle line:84%
students who were using it
for some appropriate academic

00:32:32.570 --> 00:32:33.440 align:middle line:90%
purpose.

00:32:33.440 --> 00:32:35.040 align:middle line:90%
>> And Tim Leary honestly--

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:37.040 align:middle line:84%
I don't think he ever met
a rule he didn't like.

00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:39.230 align:middle line:84%
And that rule
quickly was broken.

00:32:39.230 --> 00:32:41.270 align:middle line:84%
The Harvard
Administration found out

00:32:41.270 --> 00:32:43.190 align:middle line:90%
and summarily dismissed him.

00:32:43.190 --> 00:32:49.490 align:middle line:84%
>> And he became the apostle
preaching the religion

00:32:49.490 --> 00:32:52.310 align:middle line:90%
of psychedelic drugs.

00:32:52.310 --> 00:32:56.570 align:middle line:84%
>> We teach the science
and art of ecstasy.

00:32:56.570 --> 00:32:59.180 align:middle line:84%
We teach people how
to turn on or how

00:32:59.180 --> 00:33:01.430 align:middle line:90%
to go out of their minds.

00:33:01.430 --> 00:33:04.580 align:middle line:10%
By turn on, we
mean tune in to get

00:33:04.580 --> 00:33:08.960 align:middle line:10%
beyond your routine
ways of thinking

00:33:08.960 --> 00:33:10.700 align:middle line:10%
and acting and experiencing.

00:33:10.700 --> 00:33:14.060 align:middle line:10%
We often say that we're teaching
people how to use their head.

00:33:14.060 --> 00:33:17.377 align:middle line:84%
The point is that in
order to use your head,

00:33:17.377 --> 00:33:18.710 align:middle line:90%
you have to go out of your mind.

00:33:18.710 --> 00:33:22.480 align:middle line:90%


00:33:22.480 --> 00:33:25.090 align:middle line:84%
>> What were your feelings
when people like Timothy Leary

00:33:25.090 --> 00:33:26.290 align:middle line:90%
and Ken Kesey--

00:33:26.290 --> 00:33:30.340 align:middle line:84%
Ken Kesey with his pranksters
and Timothy Leary, obviously,

00:33:30.340 --> 00:33:32.380 align:middle line:84%
with tune in, turn
on, drop out, what

00:33:32.380 --> 00:33:35.435 align:middle line:84%
were your feelings, as the
chemist who had created this?

00:33:35.435 --> 00:33:39.050 align:middle line:10%
>> I was quite astonished,
because when I had discovered

00:33:39.050 --> 00:33:43.900 align:middle line:10%
these very deep effects of LSD,
never would I have believed

00:33:43.900 --> 00:33:46.657 align:middle line:10%
that it would be a pleasure
drug on the street--

00:33:46.657 --> 00:33:47.740 align:middle line:10%
never would have believed.

00:33:47.740 --> 00:33:51.010 align:middle line:10%
The indians believe that you
should take the mushrooms

00:33:51.010 --> 00:33:53.740 align:middle line:10%
only if you are prepared.

00:33:53.740 --> 00:33:56.770 align:middle line:10%
And then only do the
mushrooms bring you

00:33:56.770 --> 00:33:58.690 align:middle line:10%
in contact with the gods.

00:33:58.690 --> 00:34:02.770 align:middle line:10%
If you are not prepared,
then it makes you crazy,

00:34:02.770 --> 00:34:05.170 align:middle line:10%
or you may even die.

00:34:05.170 --> 00:34:08.425 align:middle line:10%
That is a belief of the
Indians based on thousands

00:34:08.425 --> 00:34:10.179 align:middle line:10%
of years of experience.

00:34:10.179 --> 00:34:13.230 align:middle line:90%


00:34:13.230 --> 00:34:17.429 align:middle line:10%
>> Drugs are subversive, and
psychedelics are the most

00:34:17.429 --> 00:34:19.350 align:middle line:10%
subversive of all the drugs.

00:34:19.350 --> 00:34:21.570 align:middle line:84%
And he was labeled
most dangerous man

00:34:21.570 --> 00:34:26.550 align:middle line:84%
in America because of these very
powerful and very subversive

00:34:26.550 --> 00:34:28.409 align:middle line:90%
drugs and ideas.

00:34:28.409 --> 00:34:31.570 align:middle line:84%
>> Many of my colleagues have
maintained a rather harsh view

00:34:31.570 --> 00:34:32.370 align:middle line:90%
of Leary.

00:34:32.370 --> 00:34:34.679 align:middle line:84%
They blame him
for the repression

00:34:34.679 --> 00:34:37.572 align:middle line:84%
of psychedelic
research in the '60s.

00:34:37.572 --> 00:34:39.030 align:middle line:84%
We shouldn't lose
sight of the fact

00:34:39.030 --> 00:34:41.580 align:middle line:84%
of the degree to which
psychedelics in the culture

00:34:41.580 --> 00:34:45.870 align:middle line:84%
were associated with a very
vigorous antiwar movement.

00:34:45.870 --> 00:34:47.850 align:middle line:10%
>> The kind of turn
on, tune in, drop out,

00:34:47.850 --> 00:34:49.517 align:middle line:10%
that phrase gets a bad rap.

00:34:49.517 --> 00:34:51.600 align:middle line:10%
But if you look at what
was happening at the time,

00:34:51.600 --> 00:34:53.969 align:middle line:10%
I think the call
was for young people

00:34:53.969 --> 00:34:56.265 align:middle line:10%
to not buy into the status quo.

00:34:56.265 --> 00:34:58.353 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:34:58.353 --> 00:35:00.770 align:middle line:10%
>> Some people talk about the
counterculture as being this

00:35:00.770 --> 00:35:03.530 align:middle line:10%
romantic, even
religious movement,

00:35:03.530 --> 00:35:06.410 align:middle line:10%
that you're talking about using
these means to free yourself up

00:35:06.410 --> 00:35:09.350 align:middle line:10%
from the distractions of the
world so that you can transcend

00:35:09.350 --> 00:35:12.320 align:middle line:10%
it and think about ultimate
questions about human

00:35:12.320 --> 00:35:13.280 align:middle line:10%
existence.

00:35:13.280 --> 00:35:16.550 align:middle line:10%
And that's really what Leary
was totally talking about.

00:35:16.550 --> 00:35:18.807 align:middle line:10%


00:35:18.807 --> 00:35:20.890 align:middle line:10%
>> What we're thinking
about is a peaceful planet.

00:35:20.890 --> 00:35:22.245 align:middle line:10%
We're not thinking
about any kind of power.

00:35:22.245 --> 00:35:24.570 align:middle line:10%
We're not thinking about
revolution or war or any

00:35:24.570 --> 00:35:25.980 align:middle line:10%
of that.

00:35:25.980 --> 00:35:27.630 align:middle line:84%
We would all like
to be able to live

00:35:27.630 --> 00:35:31.080 align:middle line:84%
an uncluttered life, a
simple life, a good life,

00:35:31.080 --> 00:35:35.041 align:middle line:84%
and think about moving the
whole human race ahead a step.

00:35:35.041 --> 00:35:36.845 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:35:36.845 --> 00:35:38.650 align:middle line:90%


00:35:38.650 --> 00:35:40.300 align:middle line:84%
>> They're taking
it in sugar cubes.

00:35:40.300 --> 00:35:41.920 align:middle line:84%
It's being dropped
into their punch.

00:35:41.920 --> 00:35:43.420 align:middle line:90%
They're going to institutions.

00:35:43.420 --> 00:35:46.921 align:middle line:84%
They're swell for the
rest of their life.

00:35:46.921 --> 00:35:47.855 align:middle line:90%
[GASP]

00:35:47.855 --> 00:35:50.660 align:middle line:90%
[SCREAM]

00:35:50.660 --> 00:35:55.730 align:middle line:90%
>> God, no, no, no, no!

00:35:55.730 --> 00:35:58.170 align:middle line:84%
>> Authorities felt they
had a public health crisis

00:35:58.170 --> 00:35:58.970 align:middle line:90%
on their hands.

00:35:58.970 --> 00:36:01.250 align:middle line:84%
And these were also
catalysts for change.

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:02.990 align:middle line:84%
And the changes
they were inducing

00:36:02.990 --> 00:36:05.600 align:middle line:84%
were often perceived in
a very threatening manner

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:06.980 align:middle line:90%
by those in authority.

00:36:06.980 --> 00:36:12.200 align:middle line:84%
>> This moral decay weakens
our resistance to the onslaught

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:15.110 align:middle line:84%
of the communist
masters of deceit.

00:36:15.110 --> 00:36:16.940 align:middle line:84%
>> We've got to do
something about this.

00:36:16.940 --> 00:36:17.750 align:middle line:90%
Don't you think so?

00:36:17.750 --> 00:36:21.250 align:middle line:90%


00:36:21.250 --> 00:36:25.870 align:middle line:10%
>> The drug war is based on
demonizing drugs and demonizing

00:36:25.870 --> 00:36:27.190 align:middle line:10%
drug users.

00:36:27.190 --> 00:36:29.620 align:middle line:84%
Nixon said that the two
main enemies that he had

00:36:29.620 --> 00:36:32.710 align:middle line:84%
were the Civil Rights
Movement and the hippies.

00:36:32.710 --> 00:36:36.280 align:middle line:84%
And so while you couldn't
criminalize the ideas

00:36:36.280 --> 00:36:37.810 align:middle line:84%
that they were
struggling for, you

00:36:37.810 --> 00:36:40.210 align:middle line:84%
could criminalize the
drugs that they were using.

00:36:40.210 --> 00:36:43.720 align:middle line:84%
>> We must wage what I have
called total war against public

00:36:43.720 --> 00:36:46.420 align:middle line:84%
enemy number one in
the United States,

00:36:46.420 --> 00:36:47.740 align:middle line:90%
the problem of dangerous drugs.

00:36:47.740 --> 00:36:50.770 align:middle line:90%


00:36:50.770 --> 00:36:54.580 align:middle line:10%
>> Richard Nixon declared war
on drugs, and Congress, in 1970,

00:36:54.580 --> 00:36:56.260 align:middle line:10%
passed the Controlled
Substance Act,

00:36:56.260 --> 00:36:58.840 align:middle line:10%
which essentially put all
serotonergic hallucinogens,

00:36:58.840 --> 00:37:02.170 align:middle line:10%
like LSD and psilocybin, into
this very restrictive category

00:37:02.170 --> 00:37:06.400 align:middle line:10%
of Schedule I, which means
highest addictive liability,

00:37:06.400 --> 00:37:08.650 align:middle line:10%
no therapeutic utility.

00:37:08.650 --> 00:37:11.440 align:middle line:84%
And that was really the
beginning of the war on drugs

00:37:11.440 --> 00:37:13.870 align:middle line:84%
that we now have for
the last 40 years, which

00:37:13.870 --> 00:37:17.360 align:middle line:90%
has created a real problem.

00:37:17.360 --> 00:37:19.910 align:middle line:84%
>> At the time, something like
123 million prescriptions were

00:37:19.910 --> 00:37:23.180 align:middle line:84%
written by psychiatrists and
doctors for tranquilizers.

00:37:23.180 --> 00:37:25.370 align:middle line:10%
And more people are
killed in car crashes

00:37:25.370 --> 00:37:29.420 align:middle line:10%
because they're drunk
then die because of LSD.

00:37:29.420 --> 00:37:33.050 align:middle line:84%
What kind of drugs are OK and
what aren't is a very political

00:37:33.050 --> 00:37:34.250 align:middle line:90%
question.

00:37:34.250 --> 00:37:37.970 align:middle line:84%
>> Abuse of hard drugs began to
replace mind-expanding agents,

00:37:37.970 --> 00:37:41.690 align:middle line:84%
and LSD faded from the culture
almost as quickly as it had

00:37:41.690 --> 00:37:42.800 align:middle line:90%
exploded into it.

00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:48.060 align:middle line:90%


00:37:48.060 --> 00:37:51.630 align:middle line:84%
By the 1970s, all remaining
psychedelic studies

00:37:51.630 --> 00:37:54.160 align:middle line:90%
had been shut down.

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:57.490 align:middle line:84%
>> In 1972, '73,
I had left school,

00:37:57.490 --> 00:38:02.170 align:middle line:84%
and I got a job as a research
assistant in a dream research

00:38:02.170 --> 00:38:05.390 align:middle line:84%
study at Maimonides
Medical Center in Brooklyn.

00:38:05.390 --> 00:38:10.480 align:middle line:84%
And my job was to stay up all
night and monitor sleep EEGs.

00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:13.480 align:middle line:84%
And every time our
subject went into a dream,

00:38:13.480 --> 00:38:16.010 align:middle line:84%
I would wake them up
over an intercom system,

00:38:16.010 --> 00:38:17.960 align:middle line:84%
ask them what was going
through their mind,

00:38:17.960 --> 00:38:19.840 align:middle line:90%
and tape record the dreams.

00:38:19.840 --> 00:38:22.990 align:middle line:84%
But this also meant I had a
lot of time during the night,

00:38:22.990 --> 00:38:25.030 align:middle line:90%
and I love to read.

00:38:25.030 --> 00:38:28.600 align:middle line:84%
And one of the researchers
in his office, he

00:38:28.600 --> 00:38:30.970 align:middle line:84%
had a tremendous collection
of books and articles

00:38:30.970 --> 00:38:32.440 align:middle line:90%
on psychedelics.

00:38:32.440 --> 00:38:34.840 align:middle line:90%
And I read voraciously.

00:38:34.840 --> 00:38:37.180 align:middle line:84%
Now, at that time,
my father was very

00:38:37.180 --> 00:38:39.850 align:middle line:84%
concerned about what he thought
was my lack of direction.

00:38:39.850 --> 00:38:42.130 align:middle line:84%
And he had told me
that when I figure out

00:38:42.130 --> 00:38:44.830 align:middle line:84%
what I wanted to do with
my life, I should call him.

00:38:44.830 --> 00:38:47.080 align:middle line:84%
It didn't matter what time
of the day or night it was.

00:38:47.080 --> 00:38:48.700 align:middle line:90%
He wanted me to call him.

00:38:48.700 --> 00:38:52.060 align:middle line:10%
So there I was, at 2 or
3 o'clock in the morning,

00:38:52.060 --> 00:38:55.190 align:middle line:10%
just so impressed by
what they had done.

00:38:55.190 --> 00:38:56.980 align:middle line:10%
I felt I wanted to do this also.

00:38:56.980 --> 00:39:00.220 align:middle line:10%
I woke him up from a deep
sleep, and I said, Dad,

00:39:00.220 --> 00:39:01.820 align:middle line:10%
I figured out what I want to do.

00:39:01.820 --> 00:39:03.550 align:middle line:84%
And he said, well,
what's that, son?

00:39:03.550 --> 00:39:06.230 align:middle line:84%
I said, I want to
study psychedelics.

00:39:06.230 --> 00:39:07.060 align:middle line:90%
Well, why is that?

00:39:07.060 --> 00:39:08.690 align:middle line:90%
Well, they're fascinating.

00:39:08.690 --> 00:39:12.580 align:middle line:84%
There's so much we could
learn about the brain, about

00:39:12.580 --> 00:39:15.040 align:middle line:84%
the mind-brain interface,
about mental illness.

00:39:15.040 --> 00:39:17.830 align:middle line:84%
And there are these
extraordinary treatment models.

00:39:17.830 --> 00:39:21.310 align:middle line:84%
And people who conventional
treatments cannot help or help

00:39:21.310 --> 00:39:22.390 align:middle line:90%
with this model.

00:39:22.390 --> 00:39:25.030 align:middle line:84%
And he said, well,
son, there might

00:39:25.030 --> 00:39:26.950 align:middle line:90%
be something to what you say.

00:39:26.950 --> 00:39:29.860 align:middle line:84%
But no one will listen
to you unless you

00:39:29.860 --> 00:39:31.300 align:middle line:90%
get your credentials.

00:39:31.300 --> 00:39:42.820 align:middle line:90%


00:39:42.820 --> 00:39:44.860 align:middle line:84%
My personal background
really has a lot

00:39:44.860 --> 00:39:49.910 align:middle line:84%
to do with Timothy Leary and the
use of psychedelics in society.

00:39:49.910 --> 00:39:53.270 align:middle line:90%
I had been born Jewish in 1953.

00:39:53.270 --> 00:39:55.430 align:middle line:84%
I was raised on stories
of the Holocaust.

00:39:55.430 --> 00:39:57.620 align:middle line:84%
And then, as a young
boy, I was involved

00:39:57.620 --> 00:40:02.080 align:middle line:84%
in going to school during
the Cuban Missile Crisis.

00:40:02.080 --> 00:40:04.090 align:middle line:84%
This idea that there
could be nuclear war

00:40:04.090 --> 00:40:09.340 align:middle line:84%
and wipe out civilization
was also very traumatizing.

00:40:09.340 --> 00:40:11.170 align:middle line:84%
The final step for
me was Vietnam,

00:40:11.170 --> 00:40:13.660 align:middle line:84%
and I was in the last
years of the lottery.

00:40:13.660 --> 00:40:17.440 align:middle line:84%
And I was a Vietnam War
protester, a draft resister.

00:40:17.440 --> 00:40:20.740 align:middle line:84%
And so I first tried
LSD in '71, but I

00:40:20.740 --> 00:40:22.340 align:middle line:90%
had a very difficult time.

00:40:22.340 --> 00:40:25.682 align:middle line:84%
And I couldn't really handle
my psychedelic experiences.

00:40:25.682 --> 00:40:27.640 align:middle line:84%
I went to the guidance
counselor at my college,

00:40:27.640 --> 00:40:29.170 align:middle line:90%
and I was so lucky.

00:40:29.170 --> 00:40:31.030 align:middle line:84%
The guidance counselor
took me seriously.

00:40:31.030 --> 00:40:34.550 align:middle line:84%
And then, he said that this
was an important exploration

00:40:34.550 --> 00:40:35.350 align:middle line:90%
that I was doing.

00:40:35.350 --> 00:40:37.270 align:middle line:84%
And he gave me a
book to read, which

00:40:37.270 --> 00:40:39.850 align:middle line:84%
was a manuscript copy
of "Realms of the Human

00:40:39.850 --> 00:40:44.050 align:middle line:84%
Unconscious, Observations from
LSD Research," by Stan Grof.

00:40:44.050 --> 00:40:46.610 align:middle line:84%
When I read this book,
everything fell into place

00:40:46.610 --> 00:40:47.410 align:middle line:90%
for me.

00:40:47.410 --> 00:40:50.500 align:middle line:84%
I saw this therapeutic
use and also

00:40:50.500 --> 00:40:52.250 align:middle line:90%
the spiritual aspects of it.

00:40:52.250 --> 00:40:54.580 align:middle line:84%
And I felt, OK,
this is a response

00:40:54.580 --> 00:40:58.010 align:middle line:90%
to the craziness of the world.

00:40:58.010 --> 00:41:01.840 align:middle line:10%
>> It seems to me that
since the French Revolution

00:41:01.840 --> 00:41:05.080 align:middle line:10%
and the Enlightenment,
man was put at the center

00:41:05.080 --> 00:41:06.670 align:middle line:10%
of the universe.

00:41:06.670 --> 00:41:10.540 align:middle line:84%
And certain difficult
notions of God,

00:41:10.540 --> 00:41:13.540 align:middle line:84%
on which one was
dependent, were put aside.

00:41:13.540 --> 00:41:17.110 align:middle line:84%
And that notion of man being
at the center of the universe

00:41:17.110 --> 00:41:20.020 align:middle line:84%
led to the industrial society
that we have around us, led

00:41:20.020 --> 00:41:22.240 align:middle line:90%
to a great deal of energy.

00:41:22.240 --> 00:41:24.130 align:middle line:84%
And the LSD experience
and what we've

00:41:24.130 --> 00:41:27.100 align:middle line:84%
been through in the
'60s has brought us

00:41:27.100 --> 00:41:30.010 align:middle line:84%
to a whole new
philosophy, that man

00:41:30.010 --> 00:41:31.810 align:middle line:84%
is not the center
of the universe,

00:41:31.810 --> 00:41:34.735 align:middle line:84%
that we're simply the
transformative energies,

00:41:34.735 --> 00:41:37.150 align:middle line:84%
and that we live in a
sort of cosmic ecology

00:41:37.150 --> 00:41:39.880 align:middle line:90%
for which we're responsible.

00:41:39.880 --> 00:41:43.750 align:middle line:84%
And this is, to my mind,
the great challenge that's

00:41:43.750 --> 00:41:47.800 align:middle line:84%
in front of us, to
take the consciousness

00:41:47.800 --> 00:41:51.010 align:middle line:84%
and the individual
headspace that we've all

00:41:51.010 --> 00:41:54.950 align:middle line:84%
managed to develop and now
begin asking ourselves,

00:41:54.950 --> 00:41:57.280 align:middle line:84%
what is it all for,
and how can we use it?

00:41:57.280 --> 00:42:04.380 align:middle line:90%


00:42:04.380 --> 00:42:07.400 align:middle line:84%
>> We're now in what you can
consider a second renaissance

00:42:07.400 --> 00:42:08.960 align:middle line:90%
of psychedelic research.

00:42:08.960 --> 00:42:12.500 align:middle line:10%
There are a handful of centers
in the US, universities

00:42:12.500 --> 00:42:14.360 align:middle line:10%
that are conducting
research studies.

00:42:14.360 --> 00:42:18.170 align:middle line:84%
Probably the reinitiation
of psychedelic research,

00:42:18.170 --> 00:42:20.360 align:middle line:84%
I would really credit
Rick Strassmann.

00:42:20.360 --> 00:42:23.180 align:middle line:84%
>> Rick Strassmann had been one
of the doctors that I'd worked

00:42:23.180 --> 00:42:23.980 align:middle line:90%
with.

00:42:23.980 --> 00:42:27.710 align:middle line:84%
And he decided that he would
submit a protocol for DMT,

00:42:27.710 --> 00:42:31.370 align:middle line:84%
looking at it as potential
cause of schizophrenia.

00:42:31.370 --> 00:42:35.870 align:middle line:84%
>> A psychotomimetic model, so
it means mimicking psychosis.

00:42:35.870 --> 00:42:38.210 align:middle line:84%
And so it's a way for
a government agency

00:42:38.210 --> 00:42:41.970 align:middle line:84%
to feel OK about funding
psychedelic research.

00:42:41.970 --> 00:42:45.320 align:middle line:84%
>> So the Pilot Drug Evaluation
Staff approved this study

00:42:45.320 --> 00:42:46.250 align:middle line:90%
in 1990--

00:42:46.250 --> 00:42:49.010 align:middle line:84%
>> --and really kind of
reinitiated the field,

00:42:49.010 --> 00:42:49.880 align:middle line:90%
I would say.

00:42:49.880 --> 00:42:52.430 align:middle line:84%
And then our work
here, Roland Griffiths

00:42:52.430 --> 00:42:54.920 align:middle line:90%
got it started not long after.

00:42:54.920 --> 00:42:59.000 align:middle line:84%
>> In 2006, the Hopkins team
set the standard for scientific

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:02.630 align:middle line:84%
rigor by publishing their
landmark study "A followup

00:43:02.630 --> 00:43:05.600 align:middle line:84%
to Walter Pahnke's and
Timothy Leary's Good Friday

00:43:05.600 --> 00:43:08.990 align:middle line:84%
experiment," concluding that
under the right setting,

00:43:08.990 --> 00:43:12.950 align:middle line:84%
psilocybin can reliably
induce a mystical experience.

00:43:12.950 --> 00:43:15.530 align:middle line:84%
>> I knew nothing
about Johns Hopkins.

00:43:15.530 --> 00:43:17.328 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know anything
about Baltimore.

00:43:17.328 --> 00:43:18.620 align:middle line:90%
I didn't know Roland Griffiths.

00:43:18.620 --> 00:43:20.210 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know any
of these characters.

00:43:20.210 --> 00:43:23.060 align:middle line:84%
And I ended up going to grad
school out in California where

00:43:23.060 --> 00:43:25.490 align:middle line:84%
we were doing a study
with meditators when

00:43:25.490 --> 00:43:28.970 align:middle line:84%
Roland's paper was published on
mystical experiences promoted

00:43:28.970 --> 00:43:30.110 align:middle line:90%
by psilocybin.

00:43:30.110 --> 00:43:31.910 align:middle line:84%
And I just remember
saying to my advisor,

00:43:31.910 --> 00:43:33.577 align:middle line:84%
I was like, that's
where I'm going next.

00:43:33.577 --> 00:43:35.690 align:middle line:84%
Katherine MacLean's
research on openness,

00:43:35.690 --> 00:43:39.170 align:middle line:84%
that was a really big deal, that
study, because it was always

00:43:39.170 --> 00:43:42.290 align:middle line:84%
thought that your personality
is your personality.

00:43:42.290 --> 00:43:44.690 align:middle line:84%
How novelty-seeking you
are and how open you are,

00:43:44.690 --> 00:43:46.940 align:middle line:84%
that's just who you are, and
those things don't really

00:43:46.940 --> 00:43:47.740 align:middle line:90%
change.

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:50.330 align:middle line:84%
But what the Hopkins
trials showed

